<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910117-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>910117-0022.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):   `What Must Be Done'</HL><DATE>01/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   MDEST</CO><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   With the advent of war in the Gulf, America is united.There will be time enough later to assess the change thatthis conflict will cause in the political life of the UnitedStates and the world. In this moment, it is right to unitebehind the American armed forces and its coalition partnersas they strive to defeat a common foe.   Let there be no doubt that Saddam Hussein is an enemy ofthe men and women who now risk their lives to thwart him. Formonths he has described in language of astonishing coarsenessand violence his intention and willingness to use his arsenalof weapons against America's soldiers, Israel and others. Toachieve this purpose, Saddam Hussein assembled an army withmodern armaments, potentially supplemented by the scourge ofchemical and nuclear weapons.</LP><TEXT>   He will not succeed. It is our conviction that theAmerican people now possess the military strength and thepolitical will to defeat Saddam's unrepentant piracy. AsPresident Bush said last night, &quot;what must be done&quot; is ensurethat men of Saddam's ilk do not throttle a free world whosefuture remains bright with promise.</TEXT></DOC>